---
// melatonin dose & timing — CONTEXT page (CHK-2.2). NOT a graded remedy and NOT a dosing instruction:
// it DESCRIBES what studies used, never what the reader should take. No tier badge, no gate chips.
// Every specific is cited to a source verified firsthand and reused from the melatonin remedy corpus
// where it fits: Ferracioli-Oda 2013 & Brzezinski 2005 (small onset effect), Auld 2017 (timing not
// sedation), van Geijlswijk 2010 (advances the clock in DSPD), Zhdanova 2001 (0.3 mg physiological
// dose ≥ 3 mg; 3 mg leaves melatonin elevated into daytime), Auger/AASM 2015 (strategically TIMED
// melatonin for DSWPD), Erland 2017 (label ≠ content). Mirrors melatonin-children.astro exactly.
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import ContextBanner from '../components/ContextBanner.astro';
import ContextSources from '../components/ContextSources.astro';
import Disclaimer from '../components/Disclaimer.astro';
import Fn from '../components/Fn.astro';

const sources = [
  {
    n: 1,
    cite: 'Ferracioli-Oda E, Qawasmi A, Bloch MH. Meta-analysis: melatonin for the treatment of primary sleep disorders. PLoS One. 2013;8(5):e63773.',
    finding:
      'pooled randomized trials: melatonin reduced the time to fall asleep by about 7 minutes and increased total sleep time by about 8 minutes versus placebo — a real but small effect, not sedation.',
    pmid: '23691095',
    doi: '10.1371/journal.pone.0063773',
  },
  {
    n: 2,
    cite: 'Brzezinski A, Vangel MG, Wurtman RJ, et al. Effects of exogenous melatonin on sleep: a meta-analysis. Sleep Med Rev. 2005;9(1):41–50.',
    finding:
      'across 17 studies, melatonin shortened sleep-onset latency by about 4 minutes and raised sleep efficiency by roughly 2%.',
    pmid: '15649737',
    doi: '10.1016/j.smrv.2004.06.004',
  },
  {
    n: 3,
    cite: 'Auld F, Maschauer EL, Morrison I, et al. Evidence for the efficacy of melatonin in the treatment of primary adult sleep disorders. Sleep Med Rev. 2017;34:10–22.',
    finding:
      'systematic review: the most convincing evidence was for reducing sleep-onset latency and for regulating sleep–wake timing (circadian problems) — a timing signal, not a sedative.',
    pmid: '28648359',
    doi: '10.1016/j.smrv.2016.06.005',
  },
  {
    n: 4,
    cite: 'van Geijlswijk IM, Korzilius HPLM, Smits MG. The use of exogenous melatonin in delayed sleep phase disorder: a meta-analysis. Sleep. 2010;33(12):1605–1614.',
    finding:
      'meta-analysis: in delayed sleep phase disorder, melatonin advanced the clock hour of sleep onset by about 0.67 hours and endogenous melatonin onset by about 1.18 hours.',
    pmid: '21120122',
    doi: '10.1093/sleep/33.12.1605',
  },
  {
    n: 5,
    cite: 'Zhdanova IV, Wurtman RJ, Regan MM, et al. Melatonin treatment for age-related insomnia. J Clin Endocrinol Metab. 2001;86(10):4727–4730.',
    finding:
      'a low, physiological 0.3 mg dose restored sleep efficiency in older adults, while a higher 3 mg dose caused lower body temperature and left plasma melatonin elevated into the daylight hours — carryover, not a bigger benefit.',
    pmid: '11600532',
  },
  {
    n: 6,
    cite: 'Auger RR, Burgess HJ, Emens JS, et al. Clinical Practice Guideline for the Treatment of Intrinsic Circadian Rhythm Sleep-Wake Disorders (AASM). J Clin Sleep Med. 2015;11(10):1199–1236.',
    finding:
      'the American Academy of Sleep Medicine gives a positive (second-tier) endorsement of strategically TIMED melatonin for delayed sleep-wake phase disorder — the timing of the dose is the operative element.',
    pmid: '26414986',
    doi: '10.5664/jcsm.5100',
  },
  {
    n: 7,
    cite: 'Erland LAE, Saxena PK. Melatonin Natural Health Products and Supplements: Presence of Serotonin and Significant Variability of Melatonin Content. J Clin Sleep Med. 2017;13(2):275–281.',
    finding:
      'lab analysis of 30 supplements: actual melatonin content ranged from 83% below to 478% above the label — so the printed milligram is not a reliable dose.',
    pmid: '27855744',
    doi: '10.5664/jcsm.6462',
  },
];
---

<Base
  title="melatonin dose and timing: what the studies used | Somnary"
  description="melatonin works more like a clock signal than a sleeping pill: trials shaved only a few minutes off sleep onset, its real leverage is on the body clock, and higher doses weren't more effective. context describing what the research used — not a dosing instruction, not a grade."
  canonical="https://somnary.vercel.app/melatonin-dose-timing"
>
  <main class="page">
    <header class="head">
      <p class="eyebrow">context · dose &amp; timing</p>
      <h1 class="title">melatonin dose &amp; timing<span class="dot">.</span></h1>
      <p class="dek">
        Melatonin works less like a sleeping pill and more like a clock signal. In trials it shaved
        only a few minutes off how long people took to fall asleep; its real leverage is on the timing
        of the body clock. And across studies, higher doses were not more effective — the benefit
        showed up at low, near-physiological amounts. This page describes what the research used. It is
        not a dosing instruction, and not a grade.
      </p>
    </header>

    <ContextBanner
      note="the right dose and time depend on the person and the reason. this page describes what studies used, not what you should take — dosing decisions belong with a clinician or pharmacist."
    />

    <p class="who">
      <span class="who-tag">who this is for</span>
      anyone trying to make sense of the 3–10&nbsp;mg products on the shelf and vague &ldquo;take at
      bedtime&rdquo; instructions, and wondering whether more, or later, is better. (describing the
      evidence — not telling you what to take.)
    </p>

    <!-- safety boundary: more is not stronger; wrong time backfires (serious) -->
    <section class="callout sev-serious" role="note" aria-label="dose and timing hazard">
      <div class="callout-head">
        <span class="sigil" aria-hidden="true">!</span>
        <p class="callout-title">more is not stronger, and the wrong time can backfire</p>
      </div>
      <p class="callout-body">
        In a controlled comparison, a low <strong>0.3&nbsp;mg</strong> dose restored normal sleep
        efficiency in older adults, while a <strong>3&nbsp;mg</strong> dose lowered body temperature
        and left melatonin elevated into the daytime — carryover, not a bigger benefit.<Fn n={5} />
        Because melatonin is a timing signal, taken at the wrong hour it can shift the clock the
        <strong>wrong way</strong>. Dose and timing for a circadian problem, in pregnancy, in children,
        or alongside other medicines are clinician conversations — this page can't set them for you.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- section 01: the claim -->
    <section class="section">
      <p class="eyebrow">section 01</p>
      <h2 class="section-title">what people assume</h2>
      <div class="prose">
        <p>
          The common belief is that a bigger dose knocks you out harder, and that you take it right at
          bedtime like any sleeping pill. The shelf reinforces it: most products start at 3&nbsp;mg and
          climb to 5 or 10&nbsp;mg, as if the milligrams were a strength dial. Both halves of that
          picture — dose as sedative strength, and bedtime as the moment — are where the evidence
          diverges from the marketing.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- section 02: what the evidence shows -->
    <section class="section">
      <p class="eyebrow">section 02</p>
      <h2 class="section-title">what the human evidence shows</h2>
      <div class="prose">
        <p>
          Pooled randomized trials show a real but small onset effect: one meta-analysis found
          melatonin shortened the time to fall asleep by about <strong>7 minutes</strong> and added
          roughly <strong>8 minutes</strong> of total sleep;<Fn n={1} /> another, across 17 studies,
          put the latency reduction near <strong>4 minutes</strong> with about a 2% gain in sleep
          efficiency.<Fn n={2} /> A systematic review concluded its most convincing evidence was for
          reducing sleep-onset latency and for circadian (body-clock) timing — not sedation.<Fn
            n={3}
          /> For a body clock that runs late, a meta-analysis found melatonin advanced the internal
          clock by about <strong>0.67 hours</strong>,<Fn n={4} /> and sleep-medicine guidelines
          endorse strategically <strong>timed</strong> melatonin for that disorder.<Fn n={6} /> On
          dose, the low end did the work: 0.3&nbsp;mg restored sleep efficiency where 3&nbsp;mg mainly
          produced daytime carryover.<Fn n={5} />
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- section 03: what it does NOT show -->
    <section class="section">
      <p class="eyebrow">section 03</p>
      <h2 class="section-title">what the evidence does <em>not</em> show</h2>
      <div class="prose">
        <p>
          The trials do not show that melatonin sedates you, that a higher dose works better, or that
          there is a single correct time that fits everyone. The onset effect is measured in minutes,
          not the knock-out that marketing implies.<Fn n={1} /><Fn n={2} /> &ldquo;Strategically
          timed&rdquo; means the right hour depends on the person's clock and the reason for use — a
          meta-analysis of one disorder is not a schedule for an individual.<Fn n={4} /><Fn n={6} />
          And none of this establishes a dose or a time that is right, or safe, for you specifically.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- section 04: dose / form / label reality -->
    <section class="section">
      <p class="eyebrow">section 04</p>
      <h2 class="section-title">dose, form &amp; label reality</h2>
      <div class="prose">
        <p>
          The doses studied cluster low — roughly <strong>0.3 to 5&nbsp;mg</strong> — while shelves
          commonly sell 3 to 10&nbsp;mg, above what the trials needed.<Fn n={5} /> Form matters too:
          immediate-release acts sooner, while prolonged-release is aimed at overnight maintenance.
          And whatever the label says, the amount in the product may not match it — independent testing
          of 30 supplements found content from <strong>83% below to 478% above</strong> the
          label.<Fn n={7} /> So the printed milligram is a starting point for a conversation, not a
          reliable dose.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- section 05: take to your clinician -->
    <section class="section">
      <p class="eyebrow">section 05</p>
      <h2 class="section-title">take these to a clinician or pharmacist</h2>
      <ul class="ask">
        <li>for my situation — jet lag, a late body clock, insomnia, something else — is melatonin a reasonable option at all?</li>
        <li>if so, what studied dose range and what timing relative to my target sleep would you suggest?</li>
        <li>immediate-release or prolonged-release — which fits the problem I'm trying to solve?</li>
        <li>could melatonin interact with my other medicines or health conditions?</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <!-- related: back to the graded hub + safety boundaries -->
    <section class="section">
      <p class="eyebrow">related</p>
      <h2 class="section-title">read next</h2>
      <ul class="related">
        <li><a href="/r/melatonin">melatonin</a> — the full evidence grade and what the trials found.</li>
        <li><a href="/melatonin-long-term">melatonin, long-term</a> — what nightly use over months and years does not tell us yet.</li>
        <li><a href="/when-to-see-a-doctor">when to see a doctor</a> — the sleep problems that need a clinician, not a supplement.</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <ContextSources sources={sources} />

    <div class="disclaimer-slot">
      <Disclaimer variant="standard" />
    </div>

    <p class="review-line">
      reviewed 2026-07-07 · found an error? <a href="/methodology#corrections">corrections →</a>
    </p>
  </main>
</Base>

